BUSINESS OF THE HOUSE

Mr. Blackmore: What is the business for tomorrow?

Mr. St. Laurent: The business for tomorrow would be third reading of the bill which has just been dealt with in committee; after that, the resolution, which is on the order paper for today, for an address to His Majesty to place before the parliament of the United Kingdom a conﬁrming statute; then the resolution dealing with the Agricultural Products Act, which is No. 4 on the order

paper today; then continuation of the debate on the measure for the continuation of cer- tain orders and regulations during the national emergency arising out of the war, which is No. 6 on today’s order paper.

Mr. Knowles: In that order?

Mr. St. Laurent: Not necessarily in that order as to the last two items I have mentioned.

At eleven o’clock the house adjourned, without question put, pursuant to standing order.
